text: It looks boring. The plot is terrible. It just seems like someone trying to cash in on social justice without actually exemplifying any of the messages represented in this film. If you want to advocate for equality, why would you try doing so by putting men down? You are essentially saying that you do not think women can raise to the standard that society holds men to, so you take them down. That is outlandish. Build women up instead of taking men down and generally representing them as sexist. If you want to diversify the cast, then why is it that you have not brought any attention to any new actors that would help diversify Hollywood? That is also outlandish if your goal is to advocate for equality. Why are you remaking a movie that was originally created by a man? If you want to bring attention to female directors, it makes no sense to steal the ideas that male directors had and just swap the genders of characters in the film. I guess all of those questions are pointless. This is a money-grab. I wish that the money invested in this movie would go towards actual aspiring female directors considering the absence of women in that field. You could have used that money to create scholarships for female film students to get through college. You could have given that money to a female graduate to produce a film. This kind of capitalization is generally unappreciated. The toast joke was alright. That is really all there is to say though. Thanks Hollywood.

text: I see everyone is upset that this is a remake from the movie "What Women Want" and they think this movie will make no money. Let me break this down, there's no problem with recreating a movie. I personally see no issue with them switching the characters, but other people do. I wouldn't say the goal of this is to empower women, because the original movie wasn't made to empower men. It seems to me that when there is a movie with a female as the lead, people often say the movie is meant to empower women. That is not the case. Doesn't it seem a little strange that when you see a movie with a man as the lead, people just see it as comedy and something entertaining, but when you see a movie with a women as the lead, people just say it's about feminism, and to empower women.This makes me upset. Why can't we all just think the same about all movies and tv shows regardless of what gender the main characters are?

text: (The Holy Spirit explained in the book of John):  ***The Holy spirit is the third person of the Godhead who exercise the power of the Father and the Son in creation and redemption. Because the Holy Spirit is the power by which believers come to Christ and see with new eyes of faith, He is closer to us than we are to ourselves. Like the eyes of the body through which we see physical things, He is seldom in focus to be seen directly because He is the one through whom all else is seen in a new light. This explains why the relationship of the Father and the Son is more prominent in the Gospels, because it is through the eyes of the Holy Spirit that the Father-Son relationship is viewed.  ***The Holy Spirit appears in the Gospel of John as the power by which Christians are brought to faith and helped to understand their walk with God: He brings a person to new birth: "That which is born of the flesh is flesh, and that which is born of the Spirit is spirit" (John 3:6); "It is the Spirit who gives life" (John 6:63); The Holy Spirit is the Paraclete, or Helper, whom Jesus promised to the disciples after His ascension. The Trinity of Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are unified in ministering to believers (John 14:16)<---And I will pray the Father, and he shall give you another Comforter, that he may abide with you for ever. (John 14:26)<---But the Comforter, which is the Holy Ghost, whom the Father will send in my name, he shall teach you all things, and bring all things to your remembrance, whatsoever I have said unto you). It is through the Helper that Father and Son abide with the disciples (John 15:26)<---But when the Comforter is come, whom I will send unto you from the Father, even the Spirit of truth, which proceedeth from the Father, he shall testify of me.  ***This unified ministry of the Godhead is also seen as the Spirit brings the world under conviction of sin, righteousness, and judgment. He guides believers in to all truth with what he hears from the Father and the Son. (John 15:26). It is a remarkable fact that each person of the Trinity serves the others as all defer to one another. The Son says what he hears from the Father (John 12:49-50). The Father witnesses to and glorifies the Son (John 8:16-18 & 50, 54); The Father and Son honor the Holy Spirit by commissioning him to speak in their name. The Holy Spirit honors the Father and Son by helping the community of believers.  ***Like Father and Son, the Holy Spirit is at the disposal of the other persons of the Godhead, and all three are one in graciously being at the disposal of the redeemed family of believers. The Holy Spirit's attitude and ministry are marked by generosity; His chief function is to illumine Jesus teaching, to glorify his person, and to work in the life of the individual believer and the church.  ***(Romans 8:9)<---But ye are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, if so be that the Spirit of God dwell in you. Now if any man (have not) (the Spirit of Christ), he is (none of his).  ***(Acts 5:32)<---And we are his witnesses of these things; and so is also the Holy Ghost, whom God hath given to them that (obey him).  ***(Hebrews 1:9)<---Thou hast loved righteousness, and hated iniquity; therefore God, even thy God, hath anointed thee with the (oil) of (gladness) above thy fellows.  ***(Are you a WISE or FOOLISH VIRGIN???):  ***(Matthew 25:3-4)<---They that were (foolish) took their lamps, and took (no oil) with them: But the (wise) took (oil in their vessels) with their lamps.  ***(Ephesians 4:30)<---And grieve not the holy Spirit of God, whereby ye are sealed unto the day of redemption.  ***(The Holy Spirit of God): Should never be pushed away, ignored, or rejected, If we would remember that the one who lives in us is God's own spirit, we would be much more selective about what we think, read, watch, say, and do. Note that Paul acknowledges that (evil thoughts) and (actions) are (temptations) even for those who are (sealed) by the (Holy Spirit).

I‚Äôm very against this, not that I‚Äôm scared all my male protagonists will be womanified and I won‚Äôt be able to relate with the characters, far from it, but actually I read a comment talking about how the 13th Doctor was a woman. (Sorry if spoilers but it happened last year c‚Äômon) she said that it‚Äôs only hurting not only feminism but women in general when we take these stories that are already awesome and just replace the men with women, because it makes it seem that women can only be awesome, if they do it in a way that people know because men made it awesome, basically trying to becoming amazing in the shadow of past males. What we should be doing is telling original stories with female characters doing original and new and funny things (if you want funny in your movie) that way women don‚Äôt need to climb a mountain that was already set by a man, but rather climb her own mountain. text: Somehow, to me this movie seemed sexist to both genders.   While it is meant to make us think the main character is discriminated based on their gender, they are unlikable by the halfway point. While I can't speak entirely, since the movie isnt out yet, the "protagonist" seems like someone who is stuck up and believes they deserve everything and more. Can't speak for the other characters, as we haven't seen any yet.  Now, as for the males, they got it a WHOLE lot worse. The trailer either portrays them as obnoxious, disgusting, dumb, or sexual. The only male character in the trailer that is portayed in a good light is the employee guy, who even then has some stereotypes put onto him.   Now, before you rage at me, I know it is a comedy, and I actually did enjoy some of the jokes shown in the trailer. I may watch the movie and change my opinions after more trailers are released. This is my opinion, and if you dont believe what I said, I respect that. Have a great day, and I hope you all enjoy the movie if you decide to watch it!

text: Geez, can the entertainment industry come up with ANY new ideas....or must EVERYTHING be a copy?  This idea was already definitively and sweetly done (no I don't mean the Mel Gibson movie from 2000) by my man Rod Serling in The Twilight Zone in (I'm guessing) around 1960.  Remember that episode where this meek and mild bank clerk of a guy (can‚Äôt recall the actor‚Äôs name but it was Darren from ‚ÄúBewitched‚Äù)....kind of a 1960 version of an unsocial nerd......throws a quarter into the coinbox of a newsstand while buying¬† a newspaper, and the coin lands in a way that it balances on its edge by itself?  And after that he can read everyone‚Äôs thoughts.....and it turns out it‚Äôs not that much of a gift.....and it starts to cause him alot of problems....except for the one lonely yet sweet and pretty secretary who works with him, who when he hears her thoughts finds out what a wonderful person she truly is inside....and that she actually likes him.  And it gives him the moral support he needs.¬† In the end, he stands up for himself, improves his job situation, gets the girl, and humbly learns a little something about life AND his fellow man and woman.  Oh, the last scene is as he‚Äôs walking past the same newsstand later that afternoon, he throws another quarter in for the paper‚Äôs evening edition and his quarters KNOCKS DOWN his quarter still standing on edge from that morning.¬† After that he can no longer read thoughts.¬† But the eight hours was all he needed to acquire a newfound wisdom, and he moves on with his life as the better man for it.¬† The last scene is him and her walking down the street arm-in-arm, on to their new life.  As with most of Twilight Zone episodes, it‚Äôs sweet, poignant, and with a strong moral lesson to the story.¬† ¬†This subject (of suddenly acquiring the power to read thoughts) has already been done to its ultimate by him 55 years ago, and I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs gonna be improved upon....least of all by this stupid piece of throw-away trash (that I suspect will NOT do well at the box office).¬† I hope the entertainment industry just lets it rest after this......it‚Äôll never be done any better than the genius Rod Serling did it 55 years ago.

text: I'm a white male and when I was 17 this black girl tried to "turn up" with all her friends while in class. They stopped the entire class to play loud music on their Obama phones and dance on the tables. The teacher couldn't do anything because she was pretty scared after the black kids screamed in her face for asking them all to sit down and stop misbehaving. They were shooting some kind of worldstar hip-hop video showing how the black kids run the school or whatever. Anyway this black girl decided to end the little music video with her pouring her drink into my bookbag (she was dancing with a 7/11 BIG GULP grape slushi). I never said much in class or had any friends, so I think my irrational thinking at the time was justified. I stalked her and her "peoples" after school, waiting for her to break off from the group and walk home by herself. When she finally did, I made sure no one was around, I was scared as fuck, but still super upset about what she had done. I krept up behind her and slammed my fist so hard into the back of her head that she went into a SEIZURE! She was drooling and everything. First I started running away, and then I came back because i was mad scared that I may have accidentally caught my first body. After she stopped shaking, she started making noises like a lama or camel or something, so I ran as fast and as hard as I could trying to find someone. When I did, I told them that a girl was having a seizure and that she needed help. I pointed to where she was at and kept looking over my shoulder as I speed walked away hoping no one would know what really happened. Anyway she came to school the next day in crutches. Turns out she thought she had a stroke and had this placebo effect to where she THOUGHT she couldn't move some parts of her body and needed crutches. That's not even the funny part, the funny part is when she tried explaining to everyone who would ask how she had a "brain aneurysm" which triggered the stroke and that the aneurysm caused a "lump" near the highest functioning part of her brain, (which was actually the swelling from my punch). On a more serious note, black people enjoy doing shit like this, torment so many kids their age, people like me, and then turn around and cry that society makes them out to be bad people.  I compare black people to honey bees and bumblebees, they all look the same, but we can't always tell which are the ones that live only to sting you.

text: I‚Äôm not sure I understand correctly - who actually believes that an idea for a movie such as this will turn out well? In my mind, only two possibilities exist:  1. The people behind this movie are out of touch with popular culture, and are unaware of the backlash against PC SJW culture (uh Trump anyone??) 2. The people behind this movie are entirely aware of the controversy this will cause, and this is, in fact, the primary reason the film was made   In any case, both explanations baffle and irritate me. This movie is trash, and no one should be subject to it. To point out the blatantly obvious, imagine this movie was made not about men, but women. One can only presume this movie was created by women, so imagine this movie was made about women, by men. It simply wouldn‚Äôt get made, but because Hollywood is interested only in money, it will happily create such drivel whilst jumping on the virtue signal bandwagon.   I look forward to a time where we look back on this whole identity politics era as surreal, hysterical, and plainly one-sided.

text: The dumbest part of the trailer is the assumption that all people think the way they speak. I don't. Granted I may be an outlier but I generally think in separated images and scenarios, voices and emotions experienced by third party puppet models of people. I can have multiple lines of thought at once and ask questions from my own subconscious through theoretical conversations of morality and behavior in order to self diagnose quirks in my personality so as to better refine my sense of self. It is disappointing that culture still believes men to be barbarians, while we enjoy carnal pleasure there is substantially more to our thought process that would confuse anyone attempting to read our thoughts. text: For anybody not aware, this movie is a parallel to the original What Women Want starring Mel Gibson and Helen Hunt.   Gibson's character was portrayed in the trailer uncaring, competitive, and entitled, who felt slighted by the decisions of upper management because the position he was due was given to some new girl, and upon receiving The Gift (through arguably terrifying/traumatizing means - he got drunk and accidentally electrocuted himself in a bathtub), decided to exploit everyone around him with it. What was not portrayed in the trailer but revealed in the full release was his self-actualization, and coming to grips with the fact that there were more important things than his career, that being a better person was more admirable than a promotion.   That's the formula this movie is going to follow. Taraji has basically already said as much. In this trailer, her character is portrayed as uncaring, competitive, entitled; the position she feels she is due is given to some new guy. She receives The Gift (through potentially terrifying/traumatizing means - she is drugged by a stranger and then goes  to a rave and at some point is knocked unconscious) and subsequently decides she is going to exploit those around her with it.  What I imagine won't be portrayed in trailers, but will be present in the final release, is the journey of self discovery and the cycle of empathy and guilt over the wrongs she's committed, just as it was in the original.   TL;DR: I get the kneejerk reaction to sensationalized content, but keep in mind that the trailer is intending to show the Wildest Of The Wild to get you to respond. To get you to be interested enough to click. If you don't like the premise, that's fine, you don't have to go see it. But try to look into the full context before you make assumptions or decisions about what the narrative is actually trying to present.

text: You know what this movie needs to be, but probably won't be?  This woman with an absolutely HORRIBLE (and very LOUD) opinion about men gains the ability to read men's minds, and at first, yeah, some of her biases are confirmed with a couple of passing thoughts about this or that guy who would "hit that".  But it isn't long before she reads the thoughts of so many men who are stressed about so many things, and they feel like they're incapable of saying anything about it to anyone. Worse yet, she learns that it's because of women like her that there are so many decent men out there who have been conditioned to HATE themselves JUST because they committed the crime of being male.  She walks away from this experience learning that it was wrong for her to judge all men like she used to just because of a few bad eggs. text: *To anyone feeling like this is only another feminist movie that turns out to be sexist towards men*  I don't think this movie was meant for every man to feel like shit, it's just about a woman who felt sabotaged in her own field of work, sports, which is a field usually considered as "manly" I think we can all agree on that. It doesn't have to mean that it's the truth everywhere in the world or in every "manly" field, but for the good advancement of the plot maybe men HAD to all be assholes here. (Or maybe it was inspired by a place of work that was actually inequal in many ways, who knows?) I'll explain myself : the real-life stories that inspire action-comedies such as this one are combined together in order to make what is a sensitive topic, here sexism but it could be racism or homophobia aswell, more shocking and therefore create more action ! Because the aim of such a movie isn't to show dramatically how women suffer in their place of work, with long scenes showing the pain and struggle of the main character in her environment. The aim is to make it funny and here, to make a women look badass ! So I think that when a topic as this one is exploited in a comedy, everything is made to look more dramatic and can then hurt men because it doesn't really take time to explore the characters' feelings. Even the woman here, I haven't seen the movie but you'll probably see her cry once and then she'll be fueled on anger for the rest of the film, that's how it goes ! So what I'm saying is that you shouldn't expect for a comedy to show you what equality is, and yes, it is a possibility that the director just missed the point of feminism, but it shouln't matter because this movie genre was never meant to show a real-life situation with real-life feelings, but only the environment's emphasised shortcomings in order to create action and make the main character evolve !

text: I see a lot of comments about how the movie demonizes men and is "feminazi" propaganda with an agenda. And it's right. The movie has an agenda: to show that men and women want the same things. Love. Respect. Understanding.  At first, while her white straight male co-worker played by Max Greenfield in the film appears to be an egotistical dumb "boy", his character is really very quiet and subtle. Ali, played by Taraji P. Henson, learns that he is a caring and team working man who kept supporting her until the very end, learning to be a team worker like him in the end. Fatherhood is shown as this beautiful thing in the film.  Her father, played by Richard Roundtree, is a very touching character who did inculcated his daughter with a fierce sense of competition, but who ultimately only wishes the best for her and is always listening.  She learns trust and compassion from her future boyfriend, played by Aldis Hodge, who is never demonized by either the film nor the characters, being a sane model of manhood and fatherhood. And Jamal, the young and passionate new basketball sensation (played by Shane Paul McGhie) is damn well played and is the thematic center point of the story. He learns to follow whaf is in his heart and not in his mind which Ali teaches him by the end through a pep talk, but she learns this lesson FROM Aldis Hodge's character, her future boyfriend. Even her assistant, played by Josh Brener, is who is her shown as being her foil in the movie, manages to score some good jokes and well thought character development. The contrast of his insecure and quiet nature with her bombastic attitude is even more highlighted when she humbles herself to let him show his talent and self confidence, acknowledging his work and qualities.  Although a couple of men are antagonists in the movie, they are shown as toxic and opportunistic people (mainly her boss, rival and the cheating husbands of her friends), highlighting the theme of cooperation and team work of the movie even more.  The jokes qre crude and can be over the top sometimes, but the emotional and romantic comedy parts did the movie justice.  3.5/5 overall  It gained its place on my shelf alongside thrthe original, What Women Want (which still is a goddamn classic hard to beat though).

text: What Women Want: legitimate message about how a self-perceived ladies' man develops introspection and sensitivity towards women by finally listening to them, learning to connect with them personally and professionally, and realising machismo is a transparent and unnecessary insecurity. Women aren't portrayed as catty, backstabbing, conniving, or superficial, but empowered, hard-working, sensitive individuals. Some women feel pressured, isolated and ignored by society to the point of suicide, and acknowledging them as real sensitive people is basic human solidarity. Written, produced and directed by women, portraying both flawed men and women as equals who can learn from each other by dropping stereotypes and communicating. Subtitle of the movie: 'He has the power to hear everything women are thinking. Finally... a man is listening.'   What Men Want: if men aren't sleazy, lecherous, flatulating fratboys, they're emasculated sexless nerds, in another woke Hollywood remake where prejudicial man-haters dilute the work of other female writers for their own vendetta. Filled with tired racial cliches and predictable testicle-crushing slapstick, this shallow world is painted as another big boy's club, where men at every level of society breathe patriarchal oppression through constant humiliation and objectification of women. In an era of soaring male isolation, disillusionment and suicide, pretending men in 2019 are adulterous 1950's caricatures is a more lucrative convenience. Telepathy isn't used to see men as flawed, struggling humans (save for enhancing female sexual prowess in a tokenistic nod to the original), but to confirm them as dictatorial robotic simpletons whose nasty urges and infidelities must be preempted and exposed to protect other women. Subtitle of the movie: 'She can hear men's thoughts. Let the games begin.'   May the predictable 'fragile small-dicked incel wrote a book about how he hates female empowerment' ad hominems commence.
